04836nam a22006015i 9780773588509DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735885097 a10.1515/97807735885092doi  a(DE-B1597)655773  a(OCoLC)842933025  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD9999.C9473bC3 2013eb 7aSOC0450002bisacsh04a306.09712231 aCampbell, Miranda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of the Basement :bYouth Cultural Production in Practice and in Policy /cMiranda Campbell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPractices -- tIntroduction: Mapping Youth Cultural Production -- tYouth Voices: Life Stories of Navigation and Negotiation -- tRegistering Bedroom Economies: Theoretical Contexts of Youth Cultural Production -- tStructures -- tDoes Youth Matter? Cultural Policy in Canada -- tMaking the Case for Culture: Youth and Cultural Participation -- tCreative Britain and the Canadian Context: Youth, Education, and Entrepreneurship -- tMontreal, City of Strife? Agitation, Negotiation, and Visions of the Scene -- tInitiatives -- tBeyond Subculture: The Role of Networks in Supporting Youth-Led Initiatives -- tCommunity-Based Models of Youth Involvement with the Creative Industries: Ignite the Americas and The Remix Project -- tConclusion: Towards a Comprehensive Youth Policy Framework to Support Youth Cultural Production -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSoulja Boy, Justin Bieber, and Tavi Gevinson are hardly representative of typical youth experiences, but their origins highlight many of the realities of youth doing independent creative work. Out of the Basement profiles the variety of youth cultural production in the twenty-first century, and asks what has - or has not - changed as youth attempt to make a living from creative works. Though any young person with a laptop might have greater means to make music, films, or publish writing than in the past, the skills necessary to make a living in today's creative industries are not taught in schools - young artists must find their own way out of their basements. Integrating cultural studies, media education, and subculture studies, Miranda Campbell profiles this process of navigation and negotiation - one largely overlooked in discussions of creative economies - through the life stories of young people who are building careers through cultural work. She considers how existing policies can impede small-scale cultural production and calls for more awareness and support of youth creative enterprise. Moving between the structures directed toward creative life and the initiatives that young people produce themselves in the absence of relevant structures, Out of the Basement offers a timely analysis of the rise of small-scale creative employment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural industries -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aCultural industrieszCanadavCase studies. 0aCultural policy -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aCultural policyvCase studies. 0aPopular culture -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aPopular culturezCanadavCase studies. 0aYouth -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aYouthzCanadavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358850940uhttps://www.degruyt